/* GENERATED by scripts/build-pendragon-motifs.cjs — do not edit by hand.
   The full cross-corpus motif union (every tale's motifs.js, merged by
   Thompson code) for the Pendragon Compare graph's "All corpus" view.
   Re-run the script after changing any tale's motifs. */
window.PENDRAGON = window.PENDRAGON || {};
window.PENDRAGON.motifsAll = [{"code":"K1810","name":"Deception by disguise","cls":"K","pwyll":{"passages":[1,2,4],"conf":"high","note":"Three layered disguises in Pwyll. (a) Arawn lays his form on Pwyll for the year of impersonation; (b) Pwyll-as-Arawn impersonates Arawn through every social interaction in the Otherworld court; (c) Pwyll, in beggar's rags and oversized foot-coverings, walks into Gwawl's feast for the badger-in-the-bag trap. <strong>Compare Sir Orfeo's K1812</strong> (king as harper at the Fairy King's gate; later as beggar at Winchester) and <strong>Sir Gawain's K1810</strong> (Bertilak as the Green Knight, Morgan as the ancient lady). All three poems deploy disguise as the central deception-mechanism — but with different moral colourings: Welsh disguise is contractual, Orfeo's is rescue-enabling, Gawain's is testing."},"manawydan":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"Llwyd approaches the gallows-hill three times in rising rank — poor scholar, mounted priest, bishop with a baggage-train — each a disguise, each pressing Manawydan to give up the mouse. The ascending splendour is itself the tell that one power is dressing three times over."},"math":{"passages":[1,4],"conf":"high","note":"Gwydion's constant method: he enters Pryderi's court as the chief of a company of bards (and again at Caer Aranrhod), and plays a gilded shoemaker at Aranrhod's gate. Cross: disguise-entries across the corpus — Cei in <em>Culhwch</em>, Pwyll's beggar, Orfeo's minstrel, Owain's ring — and, pointedly, the cobbler's bench Manawydan also takes up (see Z, the Three Gold-shoemakers)."},"gawain":{"passages":[2,3,4],"conf":"high","note":"Three masks layered: Bertilak is the Green Knight; the ancient lady is Morgan; the lady is acting at the host's direction. The poem keeps the audience inside Gawain's ignorance for two whole Fitts."},"vitamerlini":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"Ganieda presents one boy to Merlin three times — as himself, with cut hair and new clothes, and dressed as a girl — asking each time how he will die (Mvt IV). The triple-disguise test is a classic deception-pattern, here turned to a precise end: to make the true prophet's three answers (rock, tree, river) seem the contradictions of a madman, and so discredit his charge against the queen. She clears herself not by disproving the leaf but by disqualifying the witness."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 5 of the nine tales."},{"code":"Z71.1","name":"Formulistic number: three","cls":"Z","pwyll":{"passages":[1,3,4,6],"conf":"high","note":"Pwyll runs on threes at every layer. Three days of Rhiannon riding past the Gorsedd. Three failed pursuits. Three rash-promise instances. Three layered disguises (Arawn-form, Pwyll-in-Arawn-form, Pwyll-in-beggar-form). The recognition-feast at Arberth seats Pwyll, Rhiannon, and Teirnon in the central triangle. (Compare Sir Gawain's Z71.1 — three blows, three hunts, three temptations, three exchanges — pervasive at every level. Pwyll uses threes more sparingly than Gawain but more structurally than Orfeo.)"},"owain":{"passages":[5,6,8],"conf":"med","note":"The romance's threefold rhythms: the three years Owain holds the fountain (Mvt V), the three-day duel with Gwalchmei (VI), the threefold sigh that reveals Luned in the dark (VIII). Compare the pervasive Z71.1 across all four sister tales — the folktale's basic counting unit."},"orfeo":{"passages":[3,5],"conf":"high","note":"Three apparitions of the fae in the wilderness (hunt, host, dance — each reducing in martial weight). Three laments by Orfeo (at the bedside, in the wilderness, at the wordless meeting). Three harpings (wild beasts, Fairy King's court, steward's hall) with three distinct audience-effects. The poem keeps the three but does not lean on it heavily. (Compare Gawain, where Z71.1 is everywhere — three blows, three hunts, three temptations, three exchanges, three days, three kisses.)"},"gawain":{"passages":[1,3,4],"conf":"high","note":"Three blows, three days, three hunts, three temptations, three exchanges of winnings, three kisses on the third evening. The poem's arithmetic is everywhere triadic — and the triad's third member is always the one that breaks."},"vitamerlini":{"passages":[1,4,6],"conf":"med","note":"The number three structures the whole poem: the <strong>three brothers</strong> slain at Arfderydd whose death begins it (Mvt I), the <strong>threefold death</strong> and the boy shown <strong>three times</strong> (Mvt IV), the <strong>three days'</strong> fast of grief, the <strong>three laughs</strong> (the leaf, the beggar, the shoe-buyer). The triadic patterning is deeply Welsh — the literature of the <em>Trioedd</em>, the Welsh Triads, thinks in threes — and runs as a formal spine beneath the narrative."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Z</strong> · Formulas & symbols — carried by 5 of the nine tales."},{"code":"M223","name":"The rash boon","cls":"M","culhwch":{"passages":[2],"conf":"med","note":"Arthur grants whatever Culhwch will name (save a few reserved treasures) before he hears the request."},"pwyll":{"passages":[1,4,5],"conf":"high","note":"Pwyll runs on rash promises more densely than any other tale in our corpus — at least three. (a) Arawn proposes the year-exchange; Pwyll grants it; (b) Gwawl son of Clud asks Pwyll for a request before naming it, exactly parallel to Arthur granting Bertilak's terms unread in Sir Gawain Fitt I; (c) Pwyll, prompted by the nobles at Preseli, promises to take a second wife within a year if Rhiannon proves barren. <strong>The Pendragon crosswalk's M223 row now has four columns, all present</strong>. Welsh, English-romance, English-Breton-lay: every Insular wonder-tale here runs on this single Welsh-distilled architecture."},"orfeo":{"passages":[5],"conf":"high","note":"The hinge of the rescue. After Orfeo's harping, the Fairy King: <em>now aske of me what it be — largelich Ichil the pay; now speke, and tow might asay.</em> Asked in the fairest possible form — speak, and you may put it to the proof. The king does not know what he is committing to. (Compare Gawain's M223 — Arthur granting Bertilak's challenge before he hears the terms, and Bertilak's exchange-of-winnings on the same form. The motif is one of the cleanest bridges between the two poems on this site.)"},"gawain":{"passages":[1,3],"conf":"high","note":"Fired twice. First in Camelot, when whichever knight takes up the axe binds himself to terms he has not yet fully heard. Then at the castle, when Gawain and Bertilak swear the exchange-of-winnings before either knows what the other will be obliged to give."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>M</strong> · Ordaining the future — carried by 4 of the nine tales."},{"code":"A186","name":"Demoted divinity walking as character","cls":"A","pwyll":{"passages":[1,2,3,4,5,6],"conf":"high","note":"Two layers in Pwyll. (a) <strong>Rhiannon</strong> descends from the Brittonic horse-goddess <em>Rīgantonā</em> (\"Great Queen\"), Epona-cognate; her pale-white horse, her chase-without-catching, her name itself are the marks of an old divinity walking in narrative as a woman. (b) <strong>Arawn</strong> and <strong>Hafgan</strong>, two crowned kings of Annwn, are pre-Christian Otherworld powers walking as kings in their own kingdom. (Compare Gawain's A186 in Bertilak naming Morgan \"Morgne the goddess\"; Orfeo's A186 in the opening euhemerism of Pluto and Juno; Culhwch's A186 in Mabon son of Modron as Maponos.)"},"orfeo":{"passages":[1,2,5],"conf":"med","note":"Two moves in the same poem. (a) Pluto and Juno, named in the opening as Orfeo's ancestors, are immediately glossed: <em>that sum time were as godes y hold</em> — were <em>held</em> for gods, demoted by the lay's own framing from gods to ancient kings. (b) The Fairy King is named <em>king o fairy</em> without any Christian framing — a divinity in all but the word, ruling his own kingdom with his queen and court. The poem allows the pre-Christian power to stand under a fae name, where it cannot stand under the classical names."},"gawain":{"passages":[4],"conf":"spec","note":"Bertilak names Morgan \"Morgne the goddess\" at the reveal — and the Green Knight, with his colour, his holly bough, and his green horse, looks unmistakeably like a vegetation god come into a Christmas hall. Both stand at the very far edge of what a Christian poet would let a god be, in 1380."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>A</strong> · Mythological — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"D1361.17","name":"Ring of invisibility","cls":"D","owain":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"Luned's ring: turn the stone into the palm and close the hand, and the wearer cannot be seen. It carries the trapped Owain out from between the castle gates, past the household come to kill him, and lets him watch the funeral — and the Countess — unseen (Mvt IV). The classic magic-ring of romance; compare the broader D1361 magic-mist/concealment family in Insular tradition. The Welsh plays on <em>kudyaw</em>, to hide: \"as long as you hide it, it will hide you.\""},"orfeo":{"passages":[2],"conf":"med","note":"From the very middle of a locked shield-wall around the ympe-tree, the queen is twitched away in a single instant. The thousand knights see nothing. Fae-taking by sudden vanishing — no physical force, no warning, no resistance possible."},"gawain":{"passages":[3,4],"conf":"high","note":"The girdle's specific claim: \"he that hade hit\" cannot be slain. Gawain takes it on this promise — and the poem refuses to say whether the promise was true."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"F151.1","name":"Perilous path / journey to the Otherworld","cls":"F","pwyll":{"passages":[1,2],"conf":"med","note":"Pwyll's solo ride into Annwn behind Arawn's leading-figure (briefly noted: <em>he led him until he saw the court</em>) is the only Welsh entry-procession in the corpus. Less elaborated than Orfeo's three-mile cleft and Gawain's North-Welsh-and-Wirral winter ride, but conceptually the same act: the king walks alone into a Otherworld he cannot return from without permission. The Welsh narrator gives the threshold its dignity by understating it."},"orfeo":{"passages":[4],"conf":"med","note":"Three miles of dark solid stone. Orfeo spares neither stub nor stone — no physical obstacle holds him. The poet treats the impossible as a fact of geography."},"gawain":{"passages":[2,4],"conf":"high","note":"Gawain's ride: the Wirral, wolves and serpents and wodwos, ice in his armour by night, the Christmas Eve prayer that summons the castle from the wood, and the New Year's path that ends at a barrow."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"F156","name":"Threshold of the Otherworld / fae-touched boundary","cls":"F","pwyll":{"passages":[1,2],"conf":"med","note":"Glyn Cuch — the hunting-glade where Pwyll loses his companions, sees the strange pack, and meets Arawn. Less marked than Sir Orfeo's rock-cleft three miles deep or Sir Gawain's Green Chapel as a hollow barrow, but the structural role is the same: the place where the king crosses, alone, into the parallel realm. The tale uses it as the form-restoration place too: at the year's end, Pwyll meets Arawn at Glyn Cuch and they exchange forms back. The threshold is implicit in the geography, not architecturally marked."},"orfeo":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"The threshold. A great rock with a vertical cleft, three miles through solid stone, opens onto the bright country of the Otherworld. (Compare Gawain's F156 the Green Chapel as a hollow barrow with three openings — the same motif, two different terrain forms.)"},"gawain":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"The Green Chapel turns out to be a hollow grass-grown barrow with a hole at each end, beside a boiling brook — no chapel at all. The classic Celtic Otherworld-entry, slipped into the poem under a Christian name."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"F252","name":"The Otherworld and its king","cls":"F","culhwch":{"passages":[8],"conf":"med","note":"Annwn and its lord Gwyn ap Nudd; behind the whole tradition stands Avalon, the apple-isle."},"pwyll":{"passages":[1,2],"conf":"high","note":"Annwn — the Welsh Otherworld — is the most fully imagined Otherworld in our corpus. Pwyll walks into it through no marked door (only across a threshold Arawn leads him to); the court has sleeping-chambers, halls, rooms, fairest furnishings of any building, gold-shot silk court-robes, a queen <em>fairest woman he had ever seen</em>, a fully functioning protocol and household. Distinctively Welsh: no precious-stone walls, no ever-light, no levitating stones. The Otherworld here is not a different reality but a finer one, on the same architectural scale as a Welsh king's hall. (Compare Sir Orfeo's F771.6 castle of crystal with ever-light F165.6: same role-slot, opposite aesthetic vocabulary. The cross-tale Z65 row makes this contrast a real comparative observation.)"},"orfeo":{"passages":[2,3,4,5],"conf":"high","note":"A hundred snow-white knights and a hundred milk-white damsels, a Fairy King and a Fairy Queen on thrones in a tabernacle of light, a porter at the crystal gate, an inner court of courtiers, attendants, and the silent half-taken. The Otherworld is built as a real court with real protocol — which is exactly what makes it bindable."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"F567","name":"The wild man of the woods (madness in the wilderness)","cls":"F","owain":{"passages":[7],"conf":"med","note":"His word broken and his ring stripped, Owain runs mad and naked into the wastes — clothes rotting, body wasting, long hair growing over him — until he lives among the deer and even they leave him behind. The native Brittonic <em>gwyllt</em>, the wild man whose reason is lost to grief and guilt and recovered only in the wilderness: the type behind Myrddin Wyllt (Merlin) and the Irish Suibhne. The Welsh romance's distinctive deepening of the international Yvain-madness, which in Chrétien is briefer and less mythic."},"gawain":{"passages":[1,4],"conf":"high","note":"The Green Knight in the round: green skin, green hair, green beard, green clothes, green horse, green axe. The Wild Man / Green Man of folk-tradition burst into Camelot at the Christmas season — a vegetation power on his own legs, half-domesticated for a feast-game."},"vitamerlini":{"passages":[1,2],"conf":"high","note":"The keystone motif: <em>fit silvester homo</em>, \"he becomes a man of the woods\" (Mvt I). Grief unmakes Merlin's reason and he flees to the Caledonian Wood to live among the beasts, eating roots and fruit, overgrown \"after the manner of a beast.\" This is the figure the whole tradition of the medieval <strong>Wild Man</strong> grows from — the hairy <em>wodewose</em> of the misericords, the mad Tristan, the Irish Suibhne, the Scottish Lailoken — and the madness <a href=\"/owain/\">Owain</a> falls into in the wilderness. The wisdom that returns is the gift the woods give back."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"H1556","name":"Tests of fidelity — the chaste sleep variant","cls":"H","pwyll":{"passages":[2],"conf":"high","note":"Pwyll's chaste year in Annwn beside Arawn's queen is the most refined H1556 fidelity test in our corpus. The fairest woman in the Otherworld is placed in his bed with the full form of her own husband upon him; Arawn never warns him that he is being watched; no human eye observes the result. Every night Pwyll turns his face to the bed-edge and his back to her. The test is <em>passed without being declared as a test</em> — the Welsh prose simply reports the act and (at the homecoming) the queen's bewildered silence triggers the recognition. <strong>Compare Sir Gawain's H1556</strong> (the exchange-of-winnings — the test is explicit, the hero half-fails) and <strong>Sir Orfeo's H1556</strong> (the steward's seven-year loyalty — the test is the absent king's idea). Three different vectors on the same call-number: Welsh chaste-sleep, English chivalric exchange, English homecoming-test."},"orfeo":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"The steward's test in Movement VI. Orfeo, unrecognised, tells the steward the lying tale of his own death — and watches what the steward does. Total grief. <em>That was mi lord, sir Orfeo!</em> The barons must lift him with the formula <em>there is no remedy for a man's death.</em> The test passes itself. (Compare Gawain's H1556, where the exchange-of-winnings tests Gawain himself; here it is the hero who tests, and the keeper of the throne who is tested.)"},"gawain":{"passages":[3],"conf":"high","note":"The exchange of winnings — three days of paralleled hunts and bedroom encounters, a test of whether the guest will return honestly all that he has been given. Gawain passes twice and fails once, for the smallest of the three currencies."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>H</strong> · Tests & tasks — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"K811","name":"Victims lured into a house and burned (the iron house)","cls":"K","branwen":{"passages":[2,4],"conf":"med","note":"Twice in the tale a house is a trap. In the cauldron's back-story the Irish pack the giant couple into an iron house and heat it white-hot to kill them; they burst out. The motif then rhymes forward: the house the Irish build to hold Brân hides armed warriors in flour-bags. The death-trap dwelling, Insular and grim. <em>Enters in Movements II &amp; IV.</em>"},"owain":{"passages":[9],"conf":"med","note":"The Black Oppressor's hall: guests received \"with joy and honour,\" made drunk, and then slaughtered for their horses, gold and raiment, the corpses heaped in the house. The treacherous-host type — hospitality turned to ambush, the dark inversion of the tale's many gracious castles. Owain converts the house of spoil into a true hospice."},"vitamerlini":{"passages":[11],"conf":"med","note":"In the chronicle (Mvt XI), Hengist's Saxons, called together with the British nobles \"as if to join peace,\" draw hidden blades and massacre them — the Night of the Long Knives, the lured-and-slaughtered-guests motif. It comes down from Nennius into Geoffrey's <em>Historia</em> and stands here as the hinge on which Britain is lost; one of the poem's chain of treacheries, with the poison-cups that fell Vortimer and Ambrosius."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"M201","name":"Pledge given — and held on honour","cls":"M","pwyll":{"passages":[1,2,4,5],"conf":"high","note":"Multiple sealed pledges in Pwyll. (a) The year-exchange covenant at Glyn Cuch; (b) the one-blow-only rule against Hafgan, held even when Hafgan begs the second; (c) Pwyll's grant to Gwawl, held externally while Rhiannon plots to redirect it; (d) Pwyll's promise to the nobles to take counsel within the year; (e) the Gwawl release-pledge. Welsh culture's binding force of the spoken word, repeatedly demonstrated. (Compare Sir Gawain's M201 in the troth-given-on-the-axe-haft and the exchange-of-winnings covenants.)"},"orfeo":{"passages":[5],"conf":"high","note":"When the Fairy King refuses to give up Heurodis on grounds of taste, Orfeo binds him with the form: <em>yete were it a wele fouler thing to here a lesing of thy mouthe.</em> A lie from the king's mouth would be a worse loathliness than any couple. The pledge holds; the king yields. Music charmed the door open; honour walked them out."},"gawain":{"passages":[1,3],"conf":"high","note":"The form is everything. Gawain's troth on the axe-haft; his trawthe (his honour) on the exchange. The poem watches him keep two of three exchanges in form, and lose the third in fact."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>M</strong> · Ordaining the future — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"N777","name":"Adventure follows from the hunt","cls":"N","pwyll":{"passages":[1,6],"conf":"high","note":"Two such hunting-encounters in Pwyll, framing the tale. (a) The hunt at Glyn Cuch in Movement I leads to the meeting with Arawn and the year-exchange; (b) the May Eve vigil at Teirnon's stable in Movement VI is a kind of mirror-hunt (Teirnon as predator waiting for the unseen taker of his foals) that leads to the recovery of Pryderi. <strong>Compare Sir Gawain's N777</strong> (the three hunts and three temptations) and <strong>Sir Orfeo's N777</strong> (the sixty hawking ladies whose path leads through the rock-cleft). All three English-Insular tales use the hunt as a plot-engine; Pwyll's Welsh version brackets the whole tale with it."},"orfeo":{"passages":[3,4],"conf":"high","note":"The sixty hawking ladies are an Otherworld hunt; Orfeo, after a decade in the wild, laughs at the sight and follows. The hunt leads him to the wordless meeting with Heurodis and then, when the ladies ride home, straight into the rock-cleft. The hunt-as-threshold to adventure preserved cleanly."},"gawain":{"passages":[3],"conf":"high","note":"Three days of hunts, each cross-cut with a bedroom encounter — the hunt outside structurally summoning, paralleling, and paying for the test inside."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>N</strong> · Chance & fate — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"N886","name":"Recognition by family resemblance","cls":"N","pwyll":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"Teirnon, having served Pwyll years ago, looks at the seven-year-old Gwri and sees the form of Pwyll Penn Annwn — and that is the recognition that brings the boy home. <strong>The cleanest single recognition-mechanism in the four-tale corpus</strong>. Sir Orfeo's steward recognises the harp before the man (N886-by-token); Sir Gawain's Bertilak reveals himself by his own confession; Culhwch's Goreu is revealed by his mother. Pwyll's recognition is purely visual and purely familial: <em>I knew his father, and the boy looks like him</em>."},"orfeo":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"The steward recognises the harp before he recognises the man. The instrument is the through-line of the poem — the single object Orfeo refused to give up, and the single object that closes the Odyssean recognition. The hero is what he carries."},"gawain":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"\"She is even thine aunt, Arthur's half-sister.\" The poem withholds Morgan's kinship to Gawain until the reveal — and then offers it as the reason he should come back to her hall."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>N</strong> · Chance & fate — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"Z65","name":"Colour symbolism — white-and-red as the Otherworld","cls":"Z","pwyll":{"passages":[1,3],"conf":"high","note":"<strong>The most visible cross-tale colour-pattern in our corpus.</strong> Pwyll establishes the Welsh white-and-red palette as the Otherworld's signature: the Cŵn Annwn shining brilliant white with red ears (Movement I); Rhiannon on the great pale-white horse with gold-shot silk shining upon her (Movement III); the Fairy King's snow-white riders and snow-white damsels with robes as white as milk in Sir Orfeo four centuries later, descending directly from this Welsh substrate. <strong>Contrast Sir Gawain's pervasive Z65 green</strong> — the Pearl-Poet's tradition runs on the opposite palette, the green of vegetation and growth and the unworldly hue. Two Insular Otherworld traditions, two opposite chromatic conventions. Adding Pwyll lets the comparative table name this with confidence."},"orfeo":{"passages":[2,3,4],"conf":"med","note":"The Fairy King's retinue ride snow-white horses, with robes as white as milk. The Otherworld's colour is not green (Gawain's tradition) but <em>white</em> — the white of the milk-white horse, the white of the bone of the harp, the white of the crystal castle's walls. (Compare Gawain's pervasive Z65 green; Orfeo's Z65 is white. Two different fae-traditions, two different palettes.)"},"gawain":{"passages":[2,3],"conf":"high","note":"The poem loves the long catalogue: the year-and-a-day stanza in Fitt II that names every month from spring to harvest to winter; the piece-by-piece arming of Gawain; the breaking of the deer, the dressing of the boar. The folktale's delight in arithmetic, raised here to lyric."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Z</strong> · Formulas & symbols — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"Z71.5","name":"Formulistic number three","cls":"Z","manawydan":{"passages":[3,5,6],"conf":"high","note":"The branch runs on threes: three crafts (saddles, shields, shoes), three crofts of wheat, three nights of mice, three visitors to the gallows (scholar, priest, bishop). The fairy-tale triple structures the whole second half."},"math":{"passages":[2,4,6],"conf":"high","note":"The branch runs on threes: three years of beast-punishment in three shapes, three beast-sons, Aranrhod's three curses, the three englynion that call the eagle down. The fairy-tale triple structures the whole tale."},"orfeo":{"passages":[3,6],"conf":"high","note":"Ten years in the wilderness. Ten years the steward holds the kingdom. The poem's largest interval is the symmetrical decade — and what is held in faerie's stasis (Heurodis) and what is held in faithful service (the kingdom) are both held for the same length of time. The number is moral, not arithmetic."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Z</strong> · Formulas & symbols — carried by 3 of the nine tales."},{"code":"A1654","name":"Origin of a game / first played","cls":"A","pwyll":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"<em>Guare broch yg got</em> — \"the badger-in-the-bag game\" — named here for the first time. The text states the etymology explicitly: <em>ac yna gyntaf y guarywyt broch yg got</em>, \"and that was the first time the badger-in-the-bag was played.\" Welsh folklorists have evidence the game (a bagged opponent beaten with feet and clubs) was actually played in medieval Welsh courts at festivals; the tale supplies its founding story. <strong>Compare Sir Orfeo's A1450</strong> (origin of the lay, in the closing colophon) and <strong>Sir Gawain's A1654</strong> (the green sash adopted as Round Table livery). Each Insular tale closes its frame by naming a real-world afterlife — a poem, a sash, a game. The pattern is one of the cleanest <em>shared rhetorical moves</em> across our four tales."},"gawain":{"passages":[4],"conf":"med","note":"The court adopts the green sash and \"ever-more after he was honoured that hade hit\" — an aetiological closing that grounds a real (or notional) heraldic sign in this tale. (The Order of the Garter's <em>Honi soit qui mal y pense</em> appears as a scribal closing colophon in the unique manuscript.)"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>A</strong> · Mythological — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"C611","name":"The forbidden door","cls":"C","branwen":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"At Gwales the seven survivors feast fourscore years out of time, all grief forgotten and Brân's head a living guest, while two doors stand open and the third — toward Cornwall — must not be opened. Heilyn opens it, and the whole weight of memory and loss returns in an instant; the timeless idyll ends. Thompson C611, the forbidden chamber, in its noblest Insular form — a myth of the suspension and the return of sorrow. <em>Realised in Movement VI.</em>"},"manawydan":{"passages":[4],"conf":"med","note":"Manawydan's interdiction: do not enter the caer, for it is the enchanter's work. Pryderi crosses the forbidden threshold and is lost. Cross: the forbidden door at Gwales in <em>Branwen</em> (the survivors may feast undecayed until the door toward Cornwall is opened) — adjacent branches, the same tabu of the threshold that must not be crossed."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>C</strong> · Tabu / interdiction — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"D1254.1","name":"Magic wand (hudlath)","cls":"D","manawydan":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"Llwyd strikes the freed mouse with a <em>hudlath</em>, restoring her to 'the fairest young woman anyone had seen.' Cross: the same word and instrument is the enchanter's-rod of <em>Math</em> (the Fourth Branch), where Math and Gwydion transform with it — a shared magical vocabulary across the Branches."},"math":{"passages":[2,3,6],"conf":"high","note":"The branch's central instrument: Math's (and Gwydion's) <em>hudlath</em> tests Aranrhod, turns the brothers to beasts and back, and restores the eagle to a man. One object that transforms, punishes and heals alike. Cross: the same word and instrument is Llwyd's wand in <em>Manawydan</em>, which un-mouses his wife and restores the wasteland — the shared magical vocabulary of the two enchanter-branches."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"D1275","name":"Magic song","cls":"D","math":{"passages":[6],"conf":"med","note":"The three englynion Gwydion sings to call the eagle down out of the oak, branch by branch, into his lap. Poetry as power — the proof that Gwydion's bardic disguise was never only a disguise — in a tradition where the <em>cyfarwydd</em>'s craft shades into magic."},"orfeo":{"passages":[3,5,6],"conf":"high","note":"The classical core preserved: Orpheus's music charms the beasts. Sir Orfeo carries the motif through three audiences with three different effects — the wild beasts of the wilderness (gather while he plays, leave when he stops); the Fairy King's court (lay at his feet, the king's good will <em>outlasts</em> the song); the steward's hall (the harp is recognised before the man). The same gift, three resolutions; the poem's argument about what music actually does."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"D2031","name":"Magic illusion (hud a lledrith)","cls":"D","manawydan":{"passages":[2,4,6],"conf":"high","note":"The branch's master-motif, named in its own words — <em>hud a lledrith</em>, 'enchantment and illusion.' The fall of mist that wipes the inhabited world, the fort that appears where no stone stood and vanishes again, the disguises of the enchanter: all one sustained illusion, laid by one hand and lifted by one bargain."},"math":{"passages":[1,4],"conf":"high","note":"Gwydion's signature: horses, hounds and gilded shields conjured from fungus (and dissolving in a day); a whole besieging fleet raised out of nothing to frighten Aranrhod; a ship and fine leather made from seaweed. Cross: the illusion-magic (<em>hud a lledrith</em>) of <em>Manawydan</em> — the vanishing caer and the emptying mist — and the wider Welsh tradition."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"D900","name":"Magic place / fae-frequented hunting-ground","cls":"D","pwyll":{"passages":[1,3],"conf":"med","note":"Two such places in Pwyll: <strong>Glyn Cuch</strong>, the named hunting-glade where the breach with Arawn occurs and where (in Movement II) the form-restoration happens; and <strong>Gorsedd Arberth</strong>, the named mound whose custom is one of two — wounds or a marvel — and where Rhiannon first appears. Welsh tradition has distinct named threshold-sites (Annwn-touched places where the membrane is thin); both Glyn Cuch and Gorsedd Arberth are real Pembrokeshire/Carmarthenshire features still mapped today. (Compare Sir Orfeo's D1810.8 magic dream-vision under the ympe-tree; Gawain's D965 holly bough at the chapel-barrow.)"},"orfeo":{"passages":[1,2],"conf":"high","note":"The <em>ympe-tree</em> — a grafted/doubled orchard tree, two trunks twisted into one. In medieval English folk-belief such trees were known fae-frequenting spots; Heurodis sleeps under one at noon, the most dangerous hour, in the most open place. Every condition for being taken."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"F320","name":"Fairies abduct mortals to fairyland","cls":"F","pwyll":{"passages":[5,6],"conf":"high","note":"The unseen power that takes Pryderi from his cradle at midnight, and that takes Teirnon's foals every May Eve. The Welsh prose names no agent — only the action. <strong>Cognate with Sir Orfeo's F255.2</strong> (\"Fairies take at noon\"): same architecture, opposite end of the day. Welsh tradition's threshold-hour for the taking is midnight; the Pearl-Poet's century's threshold-hour is noon. Both are liminal-light times when the membrane is thinnest. Adding Pwyll to the corpus turns this from a two-tale observation into a structural Insular pattern with a chronometric component."},"orfeo":{"passages":[2],"conf":"high","note":"The poem's central act. Heurodis taken <em>with fairi forth y nome</em>. The classical Orpheus's antagonist is Death itself; Sir Orfeo's antagonist is a king of a parallel realm whose rules and protocols are intact and bindable."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"F531","name":"Giants","cls":"F","culhwch":{"passages":[4,7,8],"conf":"high","note":"Ysbaddaden whose brows must be forked up, the giant Wrnach, and the fire-breathing herdsman Custennin."},"branwen":{"passages":[1,4],"conf":"high","note":"Bendigeidfran is a giant: the wedding-feast must be held in tents, \"for no house could ever hold Bendigeidfran.\" Later he wades the Irish sea (no ship can bear him) and makes his own body a bridge for his host — <em>a fo ben, bid bont</em>, \"he who would be chief, let him be a bridge.\" The giant's scale is the hinge of the plot when the Irish build a house to hold him. Realised first in Movement I."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"F771.6","name":"Castle of crystal / precious stones","cls":"F","orfeo":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"Outer wall of clear crystal; a hundred towers stoutly battlemented; buttresses arching out of the moat in red gold; cornice carved with every manner of beast; inner chambers all of precious stones; the worst pillar of burnished gold. The poet stacks superlatives and then climaxes on the most uncanny detail — see below."},"gawain":{"passages":[2],"conf":"high","note":"Bertilak's castle materialises in the trees in answer to Gawain's prayer to Mary on Christmas Eve — \"a castle full comely, gleamed and shone\" — an enchanted hold the size of a fortress, which Gawain will leave behind two weeks later with no clear memory of its location."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"H1242","name":"Hero brings back lost person from the Otherworld","cls":"H","pwyll":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"Teirnon, not Pwyll, brings Pryderi back from where the unseen power had taken him. <strong>Distinctively Pwyll: the hero of the recovery is not the husband</strong> — Welsh tradition's only mid-story protagonist transfer in our corpus. (Compare Sir Orfeo's H1242 — the husband himself rescues the queen from Faerie through the rock-cleft. Pwyll inverts the agent.)"},"orfeo":{"passages":[5,6],"conf":"high","note":"The poem's whole task, completed in the binding-rebuke scene. The test passed not by combat or riddle but by holding the antagonist to the form of his own word."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>H</strong> · Tests & tasks — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"H1554","name":"Test of curiosity (the recognised harp)","cls":"H","orfeo":{"passages":[6],"conf":"med","note":"After the harping at the steward's feast, the steward sees the harp and recognises it before he recognises the man. He has to ask: <em>where hadestow this harp, and hou?</em> The curiosity sets up the lying tale and the steward's test."},"gawain":{"passages":[3],"conf":"high","note":"The lady's three mornings at his bedside — testing not Gawain's curiosity but his courtesy under approach. The chivalric variant of the older type."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>H</strong> · Tests & tasks — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"K1812","name":"King in disguise","cls":"K","pwyll":{"passages":[2,4],"conf":"high","note":"Two specific instances. Pwyll-as-Arawn rules Annwn for a year as if he were Arawn (the disguise is total; no chamberlain suspects). Pwyll in beggar's rags walks into Gwawl's wedding feast asking for nothing but a small bag's fill of food. Both deployments share the same Welsh principle: the king is recognised by what he <em>does</em>, not by what he wears. (Compare Sir Orfeo's K1812 in the steward-test sequence in Movement VI — the same role-slot, the same disguise as test-vehicle.)"},"orfeo":{"passages":[5,6],"conf":"high","note":"Orfeo carries three disguises in succession. (a) At the Fairy King's gate: <em>Icham a minstrel lo, to solas thi lord with my gle.</em> (b) On returning to Winchester: at the town's edge with a beggar, <em>as a minstrel of pover liif</em>. (c) Into the city in the borrowed beggar's clothes. Each disguise is sincere as a working description; none is a lie. The poet is careful."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"K1837","name":"Disguise as a beggar","cls":"K","pwyll":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"Pwyll in heavy old rags and oversized foot-coverings, with the magic bag hidden, enters Gwawl's feast at \"the start of the after-meal drinking\" — the moment chosen for maximum host-expansiveness and minimum suspicion. <strong>Sir Orfeo will reuse this exact disguise-and-timing</strong> four centuries later, walking into the steward's feast in borrowed beggar's clothes with his harp on his back. The fairy-tale pacing is precise enough in both texts to be a shared narrative grammar."},"orfeo":{"passages":[4,5,6],"conf":"high","note":"The minstrel-disguise specifically. Music is the universal passport — the porter at the Otherworld asks no further question, and the steward at Winchester welcomes every good harper for the king's sake. The same disguise opens the door of the antagonist and of the loyal servant."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"K500","name":"Death evaded by trick / legal substitution","cls":"K","pwyll":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"Gwawl, bagged and at Pwyll's mercy, pleads — <em>it is no proper death to be killed in a bag</em> — and Hyfaidd Hen and Rhiannon agree. Gwawl is released by named sureties on his oath never to seek vengeance. The Welsh court's preference for <em>legal architecture over execution</em>, in its purest form. Structurally the inverse of Hafgan's clean death-at-the-ford in Movement II — Pwyll-as-Arawn killed; Pwyll-as-himself ransomed. (Compare Sir Gawain's K500 in the green-girdle scene — the hero himself evades his own death by a similar trick, except the trick has a moral cost.)"},"gawain":{"passages":[3,4],"conf":"med","note":"Gawain's hopeful reading of the green girdle in Fitt III: a small concealment, no harm done, his life secured. The reveal in Fitt IV calls the same trick by its other names: cowardice and covetousness."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"M242","name":"Bargain at a fixed future date — blwydyn y heno","cls":"M","pwyll":{"passages":[1,2,3,4,5],"conf":"high","note":"<em>Blwydyn y heno</em> — \"a year from tonight\" — the Welsh formula appears in Pwyll <strong>at least four times</strong>: the year-exchange with Arawn, the year-and-night appointment with Rhiannon on the Gorsedd, the year-from-tonight redirection of Gwawl's claim, the year given to the nobles at Preseli to resolve the heir-question. The Welsh narrative-arithmetic of <em>year-and-a-day appointments</em> as the structural beats of plot. (Compare Sir Gawain's M242 — the Green Knight's year-and-a-day return — which is the single load-bearing instance of the same architecture in Middle English.)"},"gawain":{"passages":[1,2,4],"conf":"high","note":"A year and a day; New Year's morning at the Green Chapel. The poem keeps the calendar pressing throughout — the seasons stanza in Fitt II is built for exactly this."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>M</strong> · Ordaining the future — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"M341","name":"Death foretold by a condition","cls":"M","culhwch":{"passages":[6],"conf":"spec","note":"Ysbaddaden is fated to die when his daughter weds — which is why he fights every task."},"orfeo":{"passages":[2],"conf":"med","note":"The Fairy King's threat in the vision: come tomorrow at the ympe-tree, or be fetched and torn limb from limb. Even resistance leads to the same outcome — the bargain is one-sided. The taking is fated."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>M</strong> · Ordaining the future — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"N825.3","name":"Old person as helper at the threshold","cls":"N","orfeo":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"The Winchester beggar at the town's edge, in his narrow hut. Gives Orfeo lodging, tells him the city's news, lends him the clothes for the next morning's disguise, and houses Heurodis until she is brought into the city in procession. The smallest figure with the most door-keeping to do."},"gawain":{"passages":[2,3,4],"conf":"high","note":"Morgan le Fay in age-disguise, beside the lady, honoured at table without ever being recognised. The folktale's old woman with the answer — but here her \"help\" is the test itself."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>N</strong> · Chance & fate — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"Q40","name":"Kindness rewarded / reward refused","cls":"Q","pwyll":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"Teirnon, offered by Pwyll the fairest jewels and the best horses and the most beloved hounds for the return of Pryderi, takes none. <em>And he wanted nothing.</em> The Welsh narrator names the reward-economy in its purest form: the act of restoration is its own pay. (Compare Sir Orfeo's Q40 in the Fairy King's gold-hemmed girdle offered to Gawain — and refused — and offered to Orfeo and accepted as a token of fault. The same code, three different moral positions.)"},"orfeo":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"The steward, who held the kingdom faithfully for ten years and grieved without dissembling at the false news of Orfeo's death, is named heir to the throne in the conditional reveal. Loyalty in absence rewarded with the kingdom in fullness."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Q</strong> · Rewards & punishments — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"Q450","name":"Absence of punishment — three layers","cls":"Q","pwyll":{"passages":[2,4,5,6],"conf":"high","note":"<strong>The deepest Q-absent in our corpus.</strong> Hafgan dies by contractual single combat (not punishment, but the terms of the bargain set by Arawn). Gwawl is ransomed under named sureties (not killed, not even imprisoned, sent home wounded). The <strong>six women who lied</strong> against Rhiannon are <em>never named, never charged, never expelled, never even denounced</em> after the recognition. The lie passes without judgment once Pryderi is restored. (Compare Sir Gawain's Q450-absent for the Green Knight, who is unmasked but not condemned; Sir Orfeo's Q450-absent for the Fairy King, who is bound but not even unmasked; and Culhwch's Q450-PRESENT for Ysbaddaden, beheaded by Goreu. Pwyll takes the Welsh-and-English U-absent pattern to its furthest point.)"},"orfeo":{"passages":[5],"conf":"high","note":"The single most striking <em>absence</em> in the poem. The Fairy King is not punished; he is constrained. He yields to the binding word and the poem moves on. (Compare Gawain, where the Green Knight similarly is not punished but at least is unmasked as Bertilak; here the Fairy King's mask is also his face, and the poem accepts that he goes on being the king of a different country.)"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Q</strong> · Rewards & punishments — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"T211","name":"Faithful spouse against false accusation","cls":"T","pwyll":{"passages":[5,6],"conf":"high","note":"Pwyll's refusal to set Rhiannon aside when the six women's lie convicts her of child-murder — <em>children I know there to be to her, and I shall not separate from her</em> — is the cleanest T211 in our corpus. The marriage is held against a fully-formed legal charge. (None of Culhwch, Gawain, or Orfeo carries this exact form: Orfeo's loyalty is to a queen taken by the Otherworld, against which there is no plausible alternative; Pwyll's loyalty is to a queen the court itself has condemned.)"},"orfeo":{"passages":[3,4,5,6],"conf":"high","note":"Ten years on bark and roots without considering remarriage (<em>never eft y nil no woman se</em>); the wordless meeting where the look held and the tear fell; the journey through the cleft; the rescue; the carrying-back. The whole second half of the poem is the husband's faithfulness made action. (Note the explicit pre-emption of the classical Orphic looking-back: he does not look back, and the poet flags it: <em>right as he came the way he yede</em>.)"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"T68","name":"The bride as prize","cls":"T","culhwch":{"passages":[12],"conf":"med","note":"Olwen won by the accomplishing of the set tasks."},"orfeo":{"passages":[5,6],"conf":"med","note":"The lay's deed-prize structure preserved, with one inversion: Heurodis is not a bride newly won but a wife restored. The poem's W (in Propp's sense) is re-coronation, not wedding."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"Z","name":"The heroic catalogue","cls":"Z","culhwch":{"passages":[2,8],"conf":"med","note":"The court-list invocation and the anoethau roll — the tale's delight in the long, mounting list."},"gawain":{"passages":[3],"conf":"spec","note":"On the third morning Gawain belts the green girdle over a \"royal red cloth\" with a gold-hemmed binding. The courtly luxury palette — Christmas red and gold — receives the green sash, and is in turn folded over by it. Costume coding the poem will not let you forget."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Z</strong> · Formulas & symbols — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"Z16","name":"Onomastic etiology","cls":"Z","manawydan":{"passages":[3,6],"conf":"high","note":"The tale explains names: the blue enamel 'still called Calch Lassar' after Llasar Llaes Gyfnewid, and the colophon that calls the branch the 'Mabinogi of Mynweir and Mynordd' after the gate-knockers and ass-collars Pryderi and Rhiannon wore in bondage. Cross: the Branches' love of the naming-close — <em>Tal Ebolyon</em> in Branwen, the naming of Pryderi in Pwyll."},"math":{"passages":[1,4,6],"conf":"high","note":"Math is the most place-name-dense of the Branches: Mochdref and Mochnant and Creuwryon (the swine's road), Dinas Dinlleu (\"Lleu's fort\"), Nantlleu (\"Lleu's brook\"), Llech Gronw (the holed slab still by the Cynfael), and the owl forever named Blodeuwedd. The cycle remembers itself in the land. Cross: the naming-closes of the sister branches (Tal Ebolyon, Calch Lassar, the Mynweir colophon)."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Z</strong> · Formulas & symbols — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"Z356","name":"The unique exception: the ever-light land","cls":"Z","orfeo":{"passages":[4],"conf":"med","note":"The poet stops the catalogue of the Otherworld castle's wonders to mark the single most uncanny detail: <em>al that lond was ever light.</em> The land has no night. The stones give their own light when sun fails. The wonder named within the catalogue, separately from the catalogue's tally — Z356's classic pattern."},"gawain":{"passages":[2],"conf":"high","note":"\"And why the pentangle is proper to that prince noble, I am intent to tell you, though tarry it me shall...\" The pentangle's lines have no beginning and no end — five points, each twined into the next — and the poet names it in English the <em>endeles knot</em>. Five-times-five virtues. A symbol the poem proposes as the only candidate for the closure that the green sash, in the end, must replace."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Z</strong> · Formulas & symbols — carried by 2 of the nine tales."},{"code":"A","name":"Gods surviving as characters","cls":"A","culhwch":{"passages":[8,9],"conf":"med","note":"Mabon son of Modron is the British god Maponos; Gwyn ap Nudd is lord of Annwn, the Otherworld. Old divinities walk the tale demoted to heroes and helpers."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>A</strong> · Mythological — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"A1450","name":"Origin of a lay / craft of harping","cls":"A","orfeo":{"passages":[6],"conf":"med","note":"The closing colophon: harpers in Britain heard the marvel and made of it a lay of good liking and named it after the king. Aetiological closure folded into the song. (Compare Gawain's A1654 in the closing adoption of the green sash as Round Table livery.)"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>A</strong> · Mythological — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"A615","name":"The framing of the world: elements, zones, the orders of spirits","cls":"A","vitamerlini":{"passages":[8],"conf":"med","note":"Taliesin's cosmology (Mvt VIII): the four elements yoked in concord, heaven enclosing all \"like a shell round a nut,\" the five climatic zones, the water-cycle of cloud and rain, and the three peopled heavens with their orders of spirits (angels, airy daemons, cacodemons). This is not folk-cosmogony but the learned Platonism of the twelfth-century schools (the <em>Timaeus</em> tradition, the School of Chartres) put into a Welsh bard's mouth — interpretive, a motif of the classroom rather than the hearth."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>A</strong> · Mythological — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B16.1","name":"The devastating giant boar","cls":"B","culhwch":{"passages":[10],"conf":"med","note":"Twrch Trwyth, a king turned to a monstrous venomous boar, lays whole regions waste."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B184","name":"Otherworld swine","cls":"B","math":{"passages":[1],"conf":"med","note":"The swine of Annwn — the first pigs ever to come to Britain, sent to Pryderi by Arawn king of Annwn, \"better than the flesh of oxen.\" Prestige- and Otherworld-animals, and the bait Gwydion uses to start his war. Cross: <em>Pwyll</em> (First Branch), where Arawn and Annwn are introduced — the Otherworld gift-economy of the cycle."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B184.3","name":"The otherworld boar as lure","cls":"B","manawydan":{"passages":[4],"conf":"med","note":"The shining-white (<em>claerwyn</em>) wild boar that rises from the thicket and baits hunters and hounds to the vanishing caer. White or white-and-red beasts in the Mabinogi are always from Annwn; this one is no quarry but a deliberate lure. Cross: the white-red hounds of Annwn in <em>Pwyll</em> (First Branch), and the great hunted boar Twrch Trwyth in <em>Culhwch</em>."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B211","name":"Speaking animals","cls":"B","culhwch":{"passages":[9,10],"conf":"high","note":"The boar Twrch Trwyth and his pigs argue back; the oldest animals answer the heroes' questions through Gwrhyr."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B251.*","name":"Beasts as the madman's only companions (the grey wolf)","cls":"B","vitamerlini":{"passages":[1],"conf":"med","note":"In his first winter the wild man's one companion is a grey wolf — old, starving, past the hunt — to whom he addresses the poem's most desolate apostrophe (Mvt I). The beast-companion of the forest-madman is a shared mark of the type: the Irish Suibhne keeps his fawn and his beasts, and <a href=\"/owain/\">Owain</a> in his madness lives among the deer of the wilderness. The animal stands in for the councillors a king would have, measuring the distance from the court."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B291.1","name":"Bird as messenger (the starling)","cls":"B","branwen":{"passages":[3],"conf":"high","note":"Branwen rears a starling at her kneading-trough through three years of servitude, teaches it to know her brother, binds a letter under its wing, and sends it across the sea to Brân. The animal-messenger that brings the host of Britain to Ireland. <em>Enters in Movement III.</em>"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B301","name":"Faithful animal / the grateful lion","cls":"B","owain":{"passages":[8,9],"conf":"high","note":"The grateful lion Owain saves from a serpent, which thereafter follows him \"like a greyhound he had reared,\" hunts for him, guards his sleep, and fights at his side. Loyalty made visible — and the measure, by contrast, of the broken faith that drove Owain mad. Gives the Continental twin its title (<em>le Chevalier au Lion</em>) and this site its sigil. (No animal-helper of this grateful-beast kind in the Welsh sister-tales; cf. instead the Oldest Animals as <em>guides</em> in Culhwch — a different B-class function.) Realised in Mvt VIII, where Owain cuts the serpent free and gains the companion that fights the giant and the two pages at his side."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B32","name":"The phoenix and the natures of the birds (the bestiary)","cls":"B","vitamerlini":{"passages":[14],"conf":"med","note":"Merlin's bird-discourse (Mvt XIV) is a versified bestiary in the tradition of Isidore and the <em>Physiologus</em>: the vigilant crane with its sentinel-stone, the eagle testing its young against the sun, the carrion-scenting vulture, the self-renewing <strong>phoenix</strong> (B32) and the blood-giving <strong>pelican</strong> — the two great Christ-emblems of the bestiary — the halcyon's calm seas, the talking parrot, the woodpecker that draws out nails. Learned natural history, interpretive as folk-motif, but the bedrock of medieval animal-symbolism."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B557.*","name":"Person carried by a wild riding-beast; the Lord of the Beasts","cls":"B","vitamerlini":{"passages":[5],"conf":"high","note":"Merlin rides the lead stag to Guendoloena's wedding, driving the herds of deer, does and roes before him \"as a shepherd the sheep\" (Mvt V). The image is the iconography of the antlered <strong>Lord of the Beasts</strong> — the Celtic Cernunnos, the master-of-animals of the wild-man tradition: the madman's sovereignty over the creatures of the wood mirroring the kingship he laid down. He kills the bridegroom with the stag's own torn-off antlers, the marvel turned to murder."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B563.2","name":"Animal leads hero to the hidden","cls":"B","math":{"passages":[6],"conf":"med","note":"The bondman's sow vanishes each morning by a road no one can follow, and Gwydion, following her to Nantlleu, is led to the rotting eagle in the oak. The beast-guide who knows what people do not. Cross: the shining-white boar that lures the hunters to the caer in <em>Manawydan</em> — the animal that draws a searcher across a threshold."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B841","name":"The oldest animals","cls":"B","culhwch":{"passages":[9],"conf":"high","note":"A chain of ever-older creatures — Blackbird, Stag, Owl, Eagle, Salmon — each marking time by something vast worn away. A folk motif found the world over."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B871","name":"Devastating host of small animals","cls":"B","manawydan":{"passages":[5,6],"conf":"spec","note":"The <em>eliwlu</em>, the 'innumerable host' of mice that strips the crofts ear by ear — a ravaging swarm beyond counting. Here it is also a transformation (see D117): a war-band and a whole court shrunk to vermin, the grotesque-comic shape the enchantment's malice takes."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"B871.1","name":"Giant serpent as adversary","cls":"B","owain":{"passages":[8],"conf":"med","note":"The serpent gripping the lion's tail — the adversary Owain cuts away to earn the lion's faith (Mvt VIII)."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>B</strong> · Animals — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"C920","name":"Loss / captivity for breaking tabu","cls":"C","manawydan":{"passages":[4],"conf":"med","note":"The breach of the interdiction is punished at once: Pryderi grips the bowl and is held fast and dumb; Rhiannon, following, shares it. The violation (Propp's δ) and its instant penalty are a single motion."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>C</strong> · Tabu / interdiction — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1052","name":"Magic girdle","cls":"D","gawain":{"passages":[3,4],"conf":"high","note":"The lady's green silk lace, said to keep its wearer from any death — the wonder-object that drives the third-day failure and the fourth-day reveal."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1080","name":"Magic weapon","cls":"D","gawain":{"passages":[1,4],"conf":"med","note":"The Green Knight's axe — four foot long, gold-bound, set down in Camelot and taken up again at the chapel — carries the enchantment between the two halves of the bargain."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D114.1","name":"Transformation: men to wild beasts","cls":"D","math":{"passages":[2],"conf":"med","note":"Math turns Gwydion and Gilfaethwy, three years running, into a hind and stag, a boar and sow, a wolf and she-wolf — bound to be \"of one nature\" with the beasts they wear, and to breed as they do. Forced animal-transformation as a fitted punishment; the sexes swapped each year so each bears young."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D117","name":"Transformation: men to mice","cls":"D","manawydan":{"passages":[5,6],"conf":"med","note":"Llwyd shape-shifts his whole household — and, the third night, his wife and the ladies of his court — into the host of mice that ravages the wheat. The enchanter's signature power, and the mechanism by which a court's revenge is delivered as vermin."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1171.2","name":"Magic cauldron","cls":"D","culhwch":{"passages":[8],"conf":"med","note":"The cauldron of Diwrnach the Irishman, demanded to boil the wedding feast."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1171.3","name":"The Cauldron of Rebirth (magic cauldron)","cls":"D","branwen":{"passages":[2,5],"conf":"high","note":"<em>Pair Dadeni</em>: a cauldron from the Irish lake (with the back-story of the giant Llasar Llaes Gyfnewid and his wife, and the iron house the Irish tried to burn them in). Brân gives it to Matholwch as part of the amends for Efnisien's outrage. The central magical object of the branch. <em>Enters in Movement II.</em>"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1244","name":"Magic ointment / healing balsam","cls":"D","owain":{"passages":[7],"conf":"high","note":"The widowed Countess of the park's precious balsam, poured over the mad Owain's heart (and, by the kind maid's disobedience, over all of him), which raises him from his wasted state and heals him in three months \"fairer than before.\" The tale's instrument of grace — medicinal, not fairy; sevenscore pounds' worth, spent on a stranger. Contrast Sir Orfeo, recovered out of the Otherworld itself rather than by a salve."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1361.5","name":"Magic transformation by another's form / borrowed likeness","cls":"D","pwyll":{"passages":[1,2],"conf":"high","note":"Arawn lays his <em>pryt</em> (form) and <em>ansawd</em> (appearance) on Pwyll for a year, so that no chamberlain or officer of Annwn knows the substitution. In Dyfed, Arawn-in-Pwyll's-form rules so well the men of the country afterwards beg Pwyll not to undo the policies. The form-loan is the central magical operation of the year-exchange — a refined K1810 (deception by disguise) where the deception is unwilled and the disguise is bound by an external agent. <strong>Cognate with Sir Orfeo's K1812</strong> (king in beggar's disguise) and <strong>Sir Gawain's K1810</strong> (Bertilak as the Green Knight) — but the only one of the three where the disguise is a genuine magical transformation rather than a put-on costume."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1364","name":"Sleep- and waking-music","cls":"D","culhwch":{"passages":[8],"conf":"med","note":"The Birds of Rhiannon, that wake the dead and lull the living to sleep."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1380.0.2","name":"Magic sign on shield","cls":"D","gawain":{"passages":[2],"conf":"high","note":"The pentangle painted on Gawain's shield — the \"endeles knot\" the poet calls it in English — five points each five times tying into one. Gawain's five fives: five wits, five fingers, the five wounds of Christ, the five joys of Mary, and the five virtues of fellowship, frankness, purity, courtesy, and pity."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D150","name":"Transformation to bird","cls":"D","culhwch":{"passages":[4,10],"conf":"high","note":"Menw takes bird-shape to scout the boar's treasures, and to parley in the air."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1500.1.18","name":"Magic healing water; the marvellous springs of the world","cls":"D","vitamerlini":{"passages":[12,13],"conf":"high","note":"The new spring that breaks from the hills and lifts Merlin's madness when he drinks (Mvt XII) — the cure of the whole poem, and the culmination of its water-thread (the spring on the mountaintop in Mvt II, the springs of Taliesin's catalogue in Mvt XIII). Pointedly, the healing is explained as <em>hydrology</em>, not miracle. The marvellous-fountain motif is everywhere in Insular tradition — the storm-spring of <a href=\"/owain/\">Owain</a>'s fountain is its martial cousin; here the marvel is mercy, a water that gives a man back his mind."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D152.2","name":"Transformation: man to eagle","cls":"D","math":{"passages":[5,6],"conf":"high","note":"Struck by the spear, Lleu does not die but flies up as a wounded eagle with a dreadful scream, and roosts rotting in the high oak — the solar god (Lugus) in the world-tree. The single most striking image of the branch, and the one the englynion are sung to undo."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D153.2","name":"Transformation: woman to owl","cls":"D","math":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"Gwydion's punishment of Blodeuwedd: not death but the owl's shape, condemned to shun the day and be mobbed by all other birds, keeping her name as a curse — <em>blodeuwedd</em> is still a Welsh word for the owl. The made-woman unmade, with an etiology attached (why the birds hate the owl)."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1601","name":"Self-operating object","cls":"D","culhwch":{"passages":[8],"conf":"med","note":"The harp of Teirtu plays of itself and falls silent at a wish."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1652","name":"The unfillable bag / magic insufficient vessel","cls":"D","pwyll":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"Rhiannon's small bag, into which any quantity of food can be put without it ever becoming any fuller. The opposite of the wonder-tale's standard D1652 (\"Inexhaustible food vessel\") — same code-family, inverted purpose. The food disappears from the court as it goes in; the bag stays empty until the binding condition is met (a nobleman with land and earth and wealth stepping into it with both feet). The Welsh narrative-mathematics at its most precise: the more you put in, the more nothing happens. Pure magical economics in service of the badger-in-the-bag trap."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1652.5","name":"Inexhaustible vessel","cls":"D","culhwch":{"passages":[8],"conf":"med","note":"The hamper of Gwyddneu Garanhir feeds any number who come to it — thrice-nine men, each the food he wishes."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1711","name":"The magician","cls":"D","culhwch":{"passages":[3,4,7,10],"conf":"med","note":"Menw mab Teirgwaedd, the warband's enchanter and shapeshifter."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1711.5","name":"Female magician","cls":"D","gawain":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"\"The mistress of Merlin, many a man has she taken\" — Bertilak's account of Morgan le Fay. Pupil-lover of Merlin in the wider tradition, the source of the whole enchantment."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1810.8","name":"Magic dream-vision: warning","cls":"D","orfeo":{"passages":[1,2],"conf":"high","note":"Heurodis falls asleep at noon under the ympe-tree and wakes screaming. In the vision she has just had, the Fairy King's two scouts came to her, then the king himself with his retinue, and named the next morning at the same tree as the date of her abduction. The vision is half-prophecy and half-summons — the taking begins with the warning."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1812.5","name":"Foreknowledge read from the stars (Merlin's astrology)","cls":"D","vitamerlini":{"passages":[5],"conf":"high","note":"From his mountain Merlin reads the cleared winter sky (Mvt V): the red ray of Mars tells him a king is dead and another reigns by murder (Constantine and Conan), and the divided ray of Venus tells him his wife has remarried. Foreknowledge by the legible motion of the stars — the prophet's gift working as astronomy, the same sky-reading the seventy-doored observatory is built to serve."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1980","name":"Magic invisibility","cls":"D","culhwch":{"passages":[4],"conf":"med","note":"Menw casts a glamour so the company passes the giant herdsman unseen."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D2090","name":"Land laid waste by magic","cls":"D","manawydan":{"passages":[2,5],"conf":"med","note":"Thunder and mist empty the seven cantrefs of Dyfed — no house, no beast, no smoke, no neighbour — and the crops that do grow are reaped by night. The enchanted wasteland is unique among the Four Branches; cross: the Grail <em>terre gaste</em> of the Continental romances, a kingdom waiting to be redeemed."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D2143.1","name":"Storm produced by magic (the fountain rite)","cls":"D","owain":{"passages":[2,3,6],"conf":"high","note":"The romance's engine: pour a bowlful of the fountain's water on the great slab beside it, and a tempest of thunder, hail and lightning breaks over the wood, stripping every leaf — after which the Black Knight rides to answer. A weather-making rite tied to a place, straight from the Brittonic Otherworld stock; Chrétien's Barenton fountain in Brocéliande is its Continental cousin. First raised in Cynon's tale (Mvt II); Owain repeats the rite in Mvt III."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D2171","name":"Magic adhesion to an object","cls":"D","manawydan":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"The golden bowl on the marble slab fixes Pryderi's hands to it and his feet to the stone, and takes his speech. Cross: the wide family of sticky-traps (the tar-baby type) — but turned here into a beautiful, fatal Otherworld snare baited with gold."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D630","name":"Transformation and air-flight at will (Morgen)","cls":"D","vitamerlini":{"passages":[9],"conf":"high","note":"Morgen, chief of the nine sisters of the Isle of Apples, \"knows the art by which she can change her shape, and cut the air on new wings like Daedalus\" — at Brest, Chartres or Pavia when she wills, gliding down from the air onto our shores (Mvt IX). Shape-shifting and self-willed flight are the marks of the fay; this is the earliest portrait of Morgan le Fay, and already she is enchantress as well as healer."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D700","name":"Disenchantment","cls":"D","manawydan":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"The spell lifted at a word: the wife un-moused, and the whole wasteland restored in a glance — every herd, dwelling and neighbour back as they were at their best. The clean, total liquidation that no other branch grants."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D810","name":"Magic gift from a supernatural being","cls":"D","gawain":{"passages":[3],"conf":"high","note":"Bertilak names his wife as Morgan's agent at the reveal; the girdle comes by that channel from the goddess-aunt. A gift from the very enchantment that set the test."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D965","name":"Magic plants","cls":"D","gawain":{"passages":[1],"conf":"med","note":"The holly bough the Green Knight carries in the other hand from the axe — a winter-evergreen, sign of life in dead season, in the poem's Christmas frame an explicit emblem of survival."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"T543","name":"Woman created from flowers","cls":"D","math":{"passages":[5],"conf":"spec","note":"Math and Gwydion conjure Blodeuwedd — \"Flower-Face\" — from the blossoms of oak, broom and meadowsweet, to beat Aranrhod's curse that Lleu have no wife of any earthly race. The artificial bride, made for one man and owing no loyalty she was not given, is one of the most famous and resonant inventions in Welsh myth. (Filed under D for the conjuring; the exact Thompson code is uncertain.)"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>D</strong> · Magic — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"E64.1","name":"Resurrection by cauldron — the dead return, but dumb","cls":"E","branwen":{"passages":[2,5],"conf":"spec","note":"Cast a slain man into the Cauldron of Rebirth and by next day he rises as good a fighter as before — but mute, never able to speak again. In Ireland it is turned against the Britons, reviving the Irish dead each night, until Efnisien bursts it with his own body. Resurrection without the soul's voice: the tale's bleakest marvel. (Thompson's E64 is &ldquo;resurrection by magic object&rdquo;; the cauldron-specific decimal is our best guess, hence <em>spec</em>.) <em>Enters in Movements II &amp; V.</em>"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>E</strong> · The dead — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"E783","name":"The vital (living / talking) severed head","cls":"E","branwen":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"Mortally wounded by a poisoned spear, Brân has his own head struck off; it stays undecayed, eats, and counsels the seven survivors through a seven-year feast at Harlech (with the birds of Rhiannon) and fourscore years at Gwales, before its burial at the White Hill of London facing France, a talisman against invasion. Thompson's E783 &ldquo;vital head&rdquo; — and Brân is the motif's canonical Insular instance. The Pendragon crosswalk's severed-head row points here (the Gawain-poet's talking head is its later literary cousin). <em>Enters in Movement VI.</em>"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>E</strong> · The dead — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"A571 / D1960.2","name":"The wounded king healed in the Otherworld; the king who will return","cls":"F","vitamerlini":{"passages":[9,10],"conf":"high","note":"Arthur, mortally wounded at Camlann, is borne over the sea to Morgen on the Isle of Apples, to be healed \"if he stays a long time\" (Mvt IX) — not dead, but waiting. When Taliesin proposes recalling him, Merlin declines, setting the longer hope of Cadwallader's recovery in its place (Mvt X). This is the once-and-future king (<em>rex quondam rexque futurus</em>) in his earliest, barest form — the motif of the returning hero (cf. the sleeping king of D1960.2) that the <a href=\"/pendragon/\">Pendragon</a> hub traces to its source."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"D1810.0.2","name":"Wind-borne omniscience","cls":"F","math":{"passages":[1],"conf":"spec","note":"Math hears every whisper that passes between people, however low, \"if the wind meet it.\" The sovereign's magical hearing makes ordinary scheming impossible — which is exactly why the conspirators need something louder than a whisper: a war."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F","name":"The unreachable fort","cls":"F","culhwch":{"passages":[4],"conf":"spec","note":"The stronghold that comes no nearer however far you walk — the Otherworld holding its distance."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F111","name":"Voyage to the Isle of Apples (the earthly paradise)","cls":"F","vitamerlini":{"passages":[9],"conf":"high","note":"The <em>Insula Pomorum</em> — the Isle of Apples, the Fortunate Isle — where apples and grain grow untilled, the ground yields all things of its own accord, and men live a hundred years and more (Mvt IX). Geoffrey makes the classical Isle of the Blessed (<em>insulae fortunatae</em>) British, and it is the destination of the poem's whole apple-thread: from the nineteen vanished apple-trees of Merlin's first lament (Mvt I) to the apple-island at the world's edge. The deepest root of Avalon."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F165.6","name":"Ever-light Otherworld lit by jewels","cls":"F","orfeo":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"<em>Al that lond was ever light, for when it schuld be therk and night, the riche stones light gonne, as bright as doth at none the sonne.</em> The castle's gems give out their own light at night, as bright as noonday sun. The Otherworld has no nightfall — and the noon hour is its perpetual condition. The temporal motif of F255.2 (taking at noon) becomes the spatial condition here."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F167","name":"The shining hounds of the Otherworld","cls":"F","pwyll":{"passages":[1],"conf":"high","note":"The <em>Cŵn Annwn</em> — Arawn's hunting-pack: shining brilliant white with bright red ears, of a hue Pwyll had never seen on a hunting-dog. The founding image of the Insular spectral hound; ancestor of every white-with-red dog in British folk-tradition from medieval ghost-pack legends to Conan Doyle's <em>Hound of the Baskervilles</em>. The breach Pwyll commits at Glyn Cuch — driving them off the stag — is the act that opens the whole tale. (For the cross-tale layer, see Z65 below — the Cŵn Annwn anchor the Welsh white-Otherworld palette that <em>contrasts</em> with Sir Gawain's pervasive green.)"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F215","name":"Two contending Otherworld kings / divided realm","cls":"F","pwyll":{"passages":[1,2],"conf":"high","note":"Annwn holds two crowned kings — Arawn and Hafgan (whose name means roughly \"Summer-bright\") — whose realms march together and who are perpetually at war. Hafgan's nobles testify after his death that there is no king of all Annwn but Arawn now; the two kingdoms have always been incomplete. The Welsh Otherworld is internally divided, doubled, perpetually contested. (No exact parallel in the other three tales: Sir Orfeo's Fairy King is singular; Sir Gawain's Bertilak rules Hautdesert alone; Culhwch's Annwn is invoked through Gwyn ap Nudd alone. Distinctively Welsh.)"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F230","name":"Appearance of the fairy court in our world","cls":"F","orfeo":{"passages":[2,3],"conf":"high","note":"The retinue spills through the membrane: in Heurodis's vision, the hundred snow-white riders; in Orfeo's wilderness, three apparitions at noon (a hunt with no kill, a host with no destination, a dance with minstrelsy); and the sixty hawking ladies whose path Orfeo follows to the rock-cleft."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F232","name":"Fairy goddess / divinity-figure in fairy form","cls":"F","pwyll":{"passages":[3,4,5,6],"conf":"med","note":"<em>Rīgantonā</em> — \"Great Queen\" — the proto-Celtic etymology behind Rhiannon's name marks her as a descended divinity. The Welsh Triads, the Second and Third Branches, and continental Epona iconography all point at the horse-goddess substrate. The tale lets her function as a Welsh princess, but the chase-without-catching, the seven-year penance as the horse at the gate, and the naming-by-mother's-word are all marks of an older mythological figure under the courtly surface. (Compare A186 above for the broader euhemerism pattern in the corpus.)"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F243","name":"Single-jewel crown of the Otherworld king","cls":"F","orfeo":{"passages":[2,5],"conf":"med","note":"The Fairy King's crown is named in Heurodis's vision: <em>it nas of silver, no of gold red, ac it was of a precious ston — as bright as the sonne it schon.</em> No metal — one stone. The Otherworld king's signature regalia. Both king and queen wear the same kind of crown in Movement V, shining beyond the bearable."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F252.1","name":"The healing fay and the nine sisters (Morgen)","cls":"F","vitamerlini":{"passages":[9],"conf":"high","note":"Morgen and her sisterhood — Moronoe, Mazoe, Gliten, Glitonea, Gliton, Tyronoe, Thiten — who \"give the law by a kindly rule\" on the Isle of Apples, the chief of them \"more skilled in the art of healing\" and surpassing in beauty (Mvt IX). The nine maidens of the Fortunate Isle are an old Celtic and classical pattern (the nine priestesses of the Île de Sein); this is the <strong>earliest literary Morgan le Fay</strong>, healer before villainess."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F255.2","name":"Fairies take at noon / under-tide","cls":"F","orfeo":{"passages":[1,3,6],"conf":"high","note":"The central temporal motif. Heurodis is abducted at the noon hour. Orfeo's three apparitions in the wilderness all come <em>in hot under tides</em> — at the same hour. He enters his own city in disguise <em>ogain none tide</em> — at the same hour. Noon is the hour when the membrane between worlds is thinnest, and the poem returns to it three times for major thresholds."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F302.1.2","name":"Fairy mistress comes to live with mortal","cls":"F","pwyll":{"passages":[3,4],"conf":"high","note":"Rhiannon, the Brittonic horse-goddess walking as Hyfaidd Hen's daughter, comes <em>specifically to find Pwyll</em>, in love with him before they meet, and arranges her own deliverance from Gwawl so she can marry him. The Otherworld bride takes initiative in every direction — she is the donor, the strategist, the bride, the architect of the wedding. Most distinctive Insular bride-quest variant: not Olwen-style (won by tasks set by the giant-father), not Heurodis-style (recovered after abduction), but <em>asked correctly and chose him</em>."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F302.6","name":"Recovery of bride from Otherworld bridegroom","cls":"F","pwyll":{"passages":[4],"conf":"med","note":"An interesting inverted variant. Rhiannon is being given against her will to Gwawl son of Clud — \"Brilliance,\" a euhemerised Brythonic light-deity, opposite-number to Pwyll's Annwn-shadow — and the badger-in-the-bag is the mechanism that releases her. The Otherworld <em>bridegroom</em> (not the Otherworld <em>captor</em>) is bound by his own rash promise and his ransom-pledge. (Compare Orfeo's binding-rebuke of the Fairy King in Movement V — both poems use the antagonist's own word to release the bride.)"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F375","name":"Mortal returns from fairyland alive and unchanged","cls":"F","orfeo":{"passages":[5,6],"conf":"high","note":"Heurodis is recovered intact — no aging, no madness, no condition. The poem firmly refuses both the classical \"you lose her at the threshold\" outcome and the folk-tradition \"a hundred years have passed while you were gone\" outcome. She walks out the same lady she walked in, and the steward at Winchester is still the steward Orfeo named ten years ago."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F379.1","name":"The half-taken — body remains as if dead while self is in fairyland","cls":"F","orfeo":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"The poem's distinctive contribution to the Otherworld tradition. <em>Of folk that were thider y brought, and thought dede and nare nought</em> — thought to be dead, and weren't. Inside the castle wall: figures held in the postures they were taken in — some headless, some bound and mad, some armed on horseback, some choked while eating, some drowned, some shrivelled by fire, women in childbed, sleeping at noon. The bodies stayed in the upper world (presumably buried); the selves are held here, frozen in the instant of trauma. Not the dead. Not the damned. The half-taken."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F407","name":"The talking severed head","cls":"F","gawain":{"passages":[1],"conf":"high","note":"The Green Knight's head, held in his hand from horseback, turns its eyes on Camelot and speaks the rules of the return-match. The motif behind every prophetic-head story from Bran the Blessed onward."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F420.5","name":"The sea-child","cls":"F","math":{"passages":[3],"conf":"spec","note":"Dylan Eil Ton, baptised, makes straight for the sea and takes its nature — swimming like the best fish, no wave ever breaking beneath him. A sea-divinity in all but name, given a single haunting paragraph before his death."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F460","name":"The monstrous keeper of beasts","cls":"F","owain":{"passages":[2,3,6],"conf":"high","note":"The huge black man on the forest mound — one-eyed, one-footed, iron-clubbed — lord of the wild animals, who gather and bow at his call, and who directs the questing knight to the fountain. A threshold-guardian out of the older Insular Otherworld; the wild-herdsman type. Compare the giant Ysbaddaden's gatekeepers and the keepers of the marvels in Culhwch. Realised first in Cynon's tale (Mvt II), then again when Owain rides the same road in Mvt III — \"his size pleased Owain\" where it had only awed Cynon."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F471.2","name":"The incubus; demons begetting on women","cls":"F","vitamerlini":{"passages":[8],"conf":"med","note":"In Taliesin's discourse the cacodemons below the moon \"even assail women in coupling, and make them pregnant, begetting after a profane manner\" (Mvt VIII). The medieval incubus belief — and a quiet, dizzying self-reference: in Geoffrey's own <em>Historia</em>, <strong>Merlin himself is the son of just such an incubus</strong>. The natural philosopher Taliesin, expounding the orders of spirits, describes the very kind of being that fathered the man he is speaking to."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F511.0.4","name":"Headless man still living","cls":"F","gawain":{"passages":[1],"conf":"high","note":"After Gawain's stroke the Green Knight rises, takes up his own head, mounts, and rides out. The folklore type kept perfectly intact under the chivalric surface."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F569","name":"Persons of unusual hue","cls":"F","gawain":{"passages":[1,4],"conf":"high","note":"The Pearl-Poet writes a green man with green hair on a green horse and never explains it. The colour itself is the marvel."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F571","name":"Extremely old person","cls":"F","gawain":{"passages":[2,3,4],"conf":"high","note":"\"The auncian lady\" beside the young wife — withered, yellow-cheeked, kerchiefed to the chin, honoured above all the household. Morgan le Fay in age-disguise. The poem stages her as the doublet to her beautiful companion: light and dark, youth and age, decoy and engine."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F571.2","name":"The king whose feet must rest in a virgin's lap","cls":"F","math":{"passages":[1],"conf":"spec","note":"Math's sacral condition: save in time of war, he cannot live unless his feet lie in the lap of a virgin foot-holder. A marvel of archaic kingship — the king bound to a fragile, ritual dependence — and the one loophole (war) that Gwydion exploits to wreck everything."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F576","name":"Otherworldly speed / supernatural pursuit-eluding","cls":"F","pwyll":{"passages":[3],"conf":"high","note":"Rhiannon's pale-white horse, riding past the Gorsedd Arberth three days in succession, at a pace no pursuer on foot or on the fastest horse in the realm can match — and the faster the pursuer, the further it gets. The marvel is not in the horse's speed but in the <em>relationship</em>: pursuit itself fails. The enchantment is broken only by being asked rather than chased. <strong>A new motif Pwyll brings into the corpus</strong> — none of the three other annotated tales carries this exact form of magical pursuit-eluding. Distinctively Welsh."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F601","name":"Extraordinary companions","cls":"F","culhwch":{"passages":[3],"conf":"high","note":"Companions defined by superhuman gifts — the marvel-motif behind ATU 513."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F610","name":"Remarkably mighty man","cls":"F","culhwch":{"passages":[3,9],"conf":"high","note":"Cei goes nine days without sleep or breath, grows tree-tall, burns hot as kindling; Bedwyr's spear makes nine wounds; Cynddylig is never lost; Gwrhyr knows all tongues."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F611.3.2","name":"Prodigiously fast-growing child","cls":"F","math":{"passages":[4],"conf":"med","note":"The child Gwydion hides in the chest grows at double speed — a year old he is as big as a two-year-old, at four as big as eight. Cross: Pryderi's same uncanny acceleration in <em>Pwyll</em>, and the year-old heroes of the wider Celtic tradition (Lleu's Irish cousin Lugh among them)."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F624","name":"Mighty lifter / catches his own head","cls":"F","gawain":{"passages":[1],"conf":"high","note":"The decapitated giant retrieves his head from the floor and bears it up — a strength-marvel particular to this type, repeated in Bricriu's Feast and the analogous French texts."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F718","name":"The marvellous fountain / spring of the Otherworld","cls":"F","owain":{"passages":[2,3,5,6],"conf":"high","note":"The spring beneath the great tree, with its silver bowl on a slab — the bounded Otherworld threshold the whole tale orbits. The guardian who must be killed to be succeeded marks it as a place where office passes by combat, not inheritance — borne out in Mvt III, where Owain kills the defender and (the tale will show) takes both his widow and his post. First seen in Cynon's tale (Mvt II)."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F771.1","name":"Castle that appears / vanishes","cls":"F","manawydan":{"passages":[4],"conf":"med","note":"The 'great, lofty caer with new-built work upon it,' standing where the four had never seen stone or building, and gone again in thunder and mist with its captives inside. Cross: the Grail Castle of Continental romance, which appears to the worthy and is not found again."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"F771.4","name":"Chains rising into the air with no end","cls":"F","manawydan":{"passages":[4],"conf":"spec","note":"The golden bowl hangs by four chains 'going up toward the air, and no end to them that he could see' — a marvel that makes the vessel a thing suspended between worlds. One of the eeriest single images in the Branches."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>F</strong> · Marvels & the Otherworld — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"G312","name":"Cannibal ogre / man-eating giant","cls":"G","owain":{"passages":[8],"conf":"high","note":"The man-shaped monster of the mountain, \"no smaller than a giant,\" who kills and devours men and seizes the hospitable Earl's sons, demanding his daughter. Owain and the lion kill it (the lion's paw opening it shoulder-to-hip). The cannibal-ogre type; cf. the giant Ysbaddaden's monstrous household in Culhwch and the ogres of the international wonder-tale. Paired with the two pages at the fire as the movement's twin combats."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>G</strong> · Ogres & giants — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"G530.2","name":"Help from the ogre's daughter","cls":"G","culhwch":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"Olwen coaches the hero to out-promise her giant father — a precise and widespread motif, here at its purest."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>G</strong> · Ogres & giants — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"G610","name":"Theft of treasure from the ogre","cls":"G","culhwch":{"passages":[10,11],"conf":"med","note":"The comb, shears and razor wrested from the boar's head; the sword taken from the giant Wrnach."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>G</strong> · Ogres & giants — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"H1010","name":"Impossible tasks","cls":"H","culhwch":{"passages":[8],"conf":"high","note":"The ~40 anoethau — clear and reap a hill in one day, the magical ingredients, the comb between the living boar's ears."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>H</strong> · Tests & tasks — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"H1233","name":"Helpers perform the hero's tasks","cls":"H","culhwch":{"passages":[9,10,11],"conf":"high","note":"Culhwch himself does almost nothing; Arthur and the companions accomplish every task for him."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>H</strong> · Tests & tasks — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"H1385.1","name":"Quest for a lost person","cls":"H","culhwch":{"passages":[9],"conf":"med","note":"The search for Mabon, gone from the world since he was three nights old."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>H</strong> · Tests & tasks — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"H1561","name":"Test of valour: holding still under the blow","cls":"H","gawain":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"At the Green Chapel the test is not to strike but to stand. The third blow nicks; the first two were testing whether the heart could keep the body in place."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>H</strong> · Tests & tasks — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"H1561.2","name":"Test of valour: the fountain combat","cls":"H","owain":{"passages":[2,3,6],"conf":"med","note":"The fountain is, at bottom, a proving-ground: pour the water, raise the storm, and a champion comes to test you. It defeats Cynon (Mvt II), is overcome by Owain (III), and unhorses the whole of Arthur's household save Gwalchmei (VI). \"If you do not find trouble in that adventure, you need never seek trouble as long as you live\" — the keeper names it a test of valour outright. The same role-slot the beheading-game fills in Sir Gawain: a bounded, repeatable ordeal that measures the knight who dares it."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>H</strong> · Tests & tasks — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"H310","name":"Suitor tests / asking correctly to win the bride","cls":"H","pwyll":{"passages":[3],"conf":"high","note":"Rhiannon waits three days for Pwyll to call out the right form — <em>for the love of the man you most love, wait for me</em> — and her first reply names what was wanted: \"it had been better for the horse if you had asked me long ago.\" The bride is won by a specific speech-act, not by a feat. Welsh fae-bride suitor-test: the magic is broken by request. Compare Culhwch's H335 / G530.2 (Olwen won by the impossible tasks her father sets) — entirely different mode of suitor-test."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>H</strong> · Tests & tasks — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"H335","name":"Tasks set for the suitor","cls":"H","culhwch":{"passages":[8],"conf":"high","note":"The bride's father imposes tasks the suitor must accomplish to win her."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>H</strong> · Tests & tasks — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"H901","name":"Tasks imposed on pain of death","cls":"H","culhwch":{"passages":[8],"conf":"med","note":"Ysbaddaden sets the anoethau with death named as the price of failure."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>H</strong> · Tests & tasks — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"K","name":"Entry by a feigned craft","cls":"K","culhwch":{"passages":[11],"conf":"spec","note":"Cei gains the giant Wrnach's hall by posing as a sword-burnisher, then kills him with his own blade. (Told here in summary.)"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"K1700","name":"Bluffing the hero","cls":"K","gawain":{"passages":[1,4],"conf":"high","note":"The Green Knight's whole challenge is a bluff: he can survive what he proposes; Camelot cannot win the game as offered. The chapel sequence repeats the bluff — two feints before the nick."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"K1851","name":"Substitute capable: hero takes the king's place","cls":"K","gawain":{"passages":[1],"conf":"med","note":"Arthur rises to take the axe; Gawain rises faster, asks for the game in the king's stead, and names himself the weakest at the table — the loss of him least mattering."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"K1971","name":"Hero in disguise tests faithful servant","cls":"K","orfeo":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"The Odyssean motif — Odysseus in beggar's rags tests Eumaeus and Eurycleia in <em>Odyssey</em> XIX. Sir Orfeo executes the same logic with the same precision, with a steward instead of a swineherd. The poem is much closer here to Homer than to anything classical-Orphic."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"K2110","name":"Slander / false witness against the innocent","cls":"K","pwyll":{"passages":[5],"conf":"high","note":"The six women's coordinated false witness against Rhiannon — <em>six of us against her alone shall not fail</em>. Pwyll's deepest K-class motif and the engine of Movement V. The lie holds against Rhiannon's protests, against Pwyll's refusal to set her aside, and rules the kingdom for seven years before Teirnon's recognition unmakes it. The international ATU 712 (Calumniated Wife) cluster cited above turns on this single function."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"K2111","name":"Potiphar's wife","cls":"K","gawain":{"passages":[3],"conf":"high","note":"Wife of the host attempts the guest; the cleanest motif-label for the lady's three approaches. Gawain refuses by the politest possible means each time — and is required, by his own oath, to give the kisses to Bertilak at evening."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"K2114","name":"Mother accused of killing and eating her own child","cls":"K","pwyll":{"passages":[5],"conf":"high","note":"The specific form the lie takes: kill some of the bitch's whelps in the chamber, smear Rhiannon's hands and face with the blood, scatter the bones, and accuse her of having destroyed her own son. The bone-and-blood evidence is fabricated; the witnesses are coordinated; the accusation is unanswerable. Pwyll's only K2114 (and our corpus's only). The motif is medieval-international (cf. Geneviève of Brabant, Crescentia), but the Welsh version is distinctive in (a) using a litter of puppies as forensic prop and (b) the U-absent that follows — the false accusers are <em>never punished</em> after the recognition."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"K2213","name":"Treacherous wife learns the fatal secret","cls":"K","math":{"passages":[5],"conf":"med","note":"Blodeuwedd extracts from Lleu the one way he can be killed under a false show of fear for his safety, and betrays it to Gronw. The wife who worms out her husband's secret weakness and hands it to his enemy — the Insular cousin of an international pattern (see the ATU 590-cluster above)."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"K717","name":"Deception into a bag (the badger-in-the-bag)","cls":"K","manawydan":{"passages":[6],"conf":"med","note":"The off-stage cause of the whole branch: in <em>Pwyll</em>, Gwawl son of Clud was tricked into a magic bag at Hyfaidd Hen's court and beaten — the game of Badger-in-the-Bag. Llwyd lays the wasteland to avenge him. Cross: <em>Pwyll</em> (First Branch) — the trick whose bill comes due, a generation late, on Pwyll's son Pryderi."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"K754.1","name":"Warriors concealed in bags (the flour-bag ambush)","cls":"K","branwen":{"passages":[4],"conf":"spec","note":"The Irish hang two hundred leather bags on the pillars of the house built for Brân, an armed man in each, and tell anyone who asks that they hold meal. Efnisien, reading the trap, goes down the row crushing each hidden head through the bone — \"What is in this bag?\" \"Meal\" — and caps it with a grim englyn. The hidden-army ambush undone by a counter-deception; the death-trap house of Mvt II returned as a battlefield. (Kin to K312, &ldquo;thieves hidden in oil-casks&rdquo; / Ali Baba; the exact bag-ambush decimal is our best guess, hence <em>spec</em>.) <em>Enters in Movement IV.</em>"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"S111.4","name":"The spurned lover's poisoned apples","cls":"K","vitamerlini":{"passages":[15],"conf":"high","note":"A woman Merlin had loved and then spurned lays poisoned apples by the spring he frequents, meaning to kill him; by the accident of his own generosity (he gives them all away, keeping none) the poison falls instead on his companions, ruining Maeldin (Mvt XV). The poisoned fruit is an old and potent motif (compare the apple of Snow White, ATU 709), and it is the dark final turn of the poem's apple-thread — the fruit of plenty and of Avalon become the fruit of murder."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>K</strong> · Deceptions — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"M","name":"Geis: a binding destiny laid on the hero","cls":"M","culhwch":{"passages":[1],"conf":"med","note":"The stepmother's tynged — Culhwch shall touch no wife but Olwen. The spoken doom that starts the tale."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>M</strong> · Ordaining the future — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"M205","name":"Breaking a pledge / hidden default","cls":"M","gawain":{"passages":[3,4],"conf":"high","note":"The girdle held back at the third evening — a default tiny in size, total in kind. The poem stages it as the precise opposite of breaking the pledge openly: Gawain keeps the form of the bargain (kisses given) while breaking its substance (a withheld piece of silk)."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>M</strong> · Ordaining the future — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"M221","name":"The Beheading bargain","cls":"M","gawain":{"passages":[1,4],"conf":"high","note":"The poem's primary engine. Two strokes, one given and one promised, a year and a day apart. Inherited from <em>Fled Bricrenn</em> via French intermediaries; preserved here in its full original shape — speaking head and all."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>M</strong> · Ordaining the future — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"M301","name":"The prophet foretells the realm's future; the recovery prophecy","cls":"M","vitamerlini":{"passages":[7,10,15],"conf":"high","note":"Merlin's gift as public vaticination: the long animal-cipher prophecy of the kings of Britain from the seventy-doored observatory (Mvt VII), in the manner of Geoffrey's own <em>Prophetiae Merlini</em>; the messianic <strong>recovery prophecy</strong> of Cadwallader and Conan who will renew \"the time of Brutus\" (Mvt X) — the Welsh <em>mab darogan</em> tradition of <em>Armes Prydein</em>; and, at the close, the passing of the prophetic gift to <strong>Ganieda</strong>, who speaks the poem's last prophecy (Mvt XV), exactly as Gwenddydd keeps Myrddin's prophecies in the Welsh <em>Cyfoesi</em>."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>M</strong> · Ordaining the future — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"M312","name":"Prophecy: the hero will overcome","cls":"M","owain":{"passages":[9],"conf":"high","note":"<em>Darogan oed dy dyuot ti yma y'm darestwng i</em> — \"it was foretold you would come here to subdue me,\" says the Black Oppressor as he yields. The romance hero arrives already written into the future of the place he mends; cf. the prophetic frame of <em>Culhwch</em> (Olwen destined for Culhwch) and the darogan-tradition of Welsh vaticination generally."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>M</strong> · Ordaining the future — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"M341.2.4","name":"The threefold death foretold (fall, hanging, drowning)","cls":"M","vitamerlini":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"Merlin foretells that the boy will die by a fall from a rock, in a tree, and by drowning — and years later, grown and hunting a stag, the boy falls from a crag, hangs by his foot from a tree, and drowns head-down in the river, all three at once, \"making the seer true through the threefold peril\" (Mvt IV). One of the most-studied of Indo-European mythic patterns, the death by three elements; in the British wild-prophet tradition it is the seer's own fate (Lailoken, Myrddin), which Geoffrey displaces onto the boy."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>M</strong> · Ordaining the future — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"N339","name":"The one vulnerable adversary","cls":"N","manawydan":{"passages":[5,6],"conf":"spec","note":"Of an innumerable host, exactly one mouse is too heavy and slow to escape — the enchanter's pregnant wife. That single accident of nature is the one flaw in a flawless enchantment, and the whole salvation of a kingdom hangs on it. Fate hands the patient man his one catchable hostage."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>N</strong> · Chance & fate — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"N456","name":"The seer's enigmatic laugh reveals hidden knowledge","cls":"N","vitamerlini":{"passages":[3,6],"conf":"high","note":"Merlin laughs at what he alone can see: the leaf in the queen's hair that betrays her tryst (Mvt III), the beggar sitting on a buried hoard, the man buying shoes he will never wear because he is already drowned (Mvt VI). Each laugh is an involuntary eruption of second sight, demanding to be explained — and the explanation drags a hidden truth into the open. The motif is widespread (the laughing angel of ATU 759, the riddling Marcolf); it is the mainspring of the poem's whole comic-uncanny middle."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>N</strong> · Chance & fate — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"N511","name":"Treasure in the ground (the beggar on the hoard)","cls":"N","vitamerlini":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"The cause of Merlin's first market-laugh (Mvt VI): a doorkeeper begs in thin clothing for the price of a cloak while sitting, all unknowing, on \"hidden heaps of coins.\" \"Turn the earth beneath him: you will find money kept there a long time.\" Hidden wealth beneath apparent poverty — the buried-treasure motif, and the mirror of the second laugh's hidden death beneath ordinary provision."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>N</strong> · Chance & fate — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"N881","name":"Foundling raised by host until recognition","cls":"N","pwyll":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"The swaddled boy in fine silk at Teirnon's door, raised in the foster-family with no knowledge of his origin, returned at seven on the strength of facial resemblance — the international foundling-cluster (N810–N881) in its most economical Welsh form. The foster-mother who raises him with full love and gives him back with the longest grief — <em>there is no one in the world with greater grief for him in her wake</em> — is the heart of the motif."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>N</strong> · Chance & fate — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"P50","name":"Noble incognito masters humble crafts","cls":"P","manawydan":{"passages":[3,5],"conf":"spec","note":"The rightful king of Britain lives as saddler, shieldwright and cobbler, mastering each trade with otherworldly skill and earning the Triadic title of one of the Three Gold-shoemakers. The dispossessed prince who will not stand on his dignity — and whose refusal to be shamed by rank is, in the end, exactly what defeats the enchanter."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>P</strong> · Society — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"Q261","name":"Treachery punished","cls":"Q","math":{"passages":[6],"conf":"high","note":"Both betrayers are punished in the reckoning: Blodeuwedd into an owl, Gronw by the return-blow. And Gronw's war-band, who refuse to take the blow for their lord, earn a place in the Triads as one of the Three Disloyal War-Bands of Britain."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Q</strong> · Rewards & punishments — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"Q281","name":"Mercy; punishment withheld","cls":"Q","manawydan":{"passages":[6],"conf":"med","note":"Holding every card, Manawydan asks not for vengeance but for guarantees — the captives freed, the spell lifted, and a binding promise of no future revenge on anyone. The villain is spared. Mercy, written as the last clause of the contract, ends the cycle of revenge the First Branch began; cross: the contrast with the genre's (and Branwen's) appetite for punishment."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Q</strong> · Rewards & punishments — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"Q331","name":"Pride punished","cls":"Q","gawain":{"passages":[4],"conf":"med","note":"The pentangle-knight, the most faultless on foot, slips on the smallest possible count — and is shown that the very perfection he pledged to was the place exposure could find. The poem refuses to call this anything but proper."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Q</strong> · Rewards & punishments — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"Q581","name":"Punishment fitting the crime","cls":"Q","gawain":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"One nick for one concealment. \"At the third thou failedst — and therefore that tap take to thee.\" The third blow's measure is the exact measure of the third evening's lie."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Q</strong> · Rewards & punishments — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"Q582","name":"Punishment fitted to the crime (talion)","cls":"Q","math":{"passages":[2,6],"conf":"high","note":"The branch's signature: a sexual violation answered by enforced bestial breeding and the shame of bearing young; and a spear-cast answered by the <em>exact</em> return-blow, Gronw made to stand where Lleu stood. Justice as precise symmetry — the work the wonder-tale usually gives to a wedding."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Q</strong> · Rewards & punishments — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"Q584.1","name":"Visible mark left for a sin","cls":"Q","gawain":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"The wound on the neck and the green sash bound under the left arm — Gawain leaves the Green Chapel marked twice: once in flesh, once in silk. Both are confessions in another shape."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Q</strong> · Rewards & punishments — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"S062","name":"The ravisher; violation of the foot-holder","cls":"S","math":{"passages":[1,2],"conf":"spec","note":"Gilfaethwy's rape of Goewin — the core villainy of the first two movements, and a crime against three things at once: her person, the sacral office of the virgin foot-holder, and the king's honour and very life-condition. The tale names it plainly and answers it doubly: amends to Goewin, the beast-punishment to the brothers."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>S</strong> · Unnatural cruelty — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"S302","name":"Murder of a child (cast into the fire)","cls":"S","branwen":{"passages":[5],"conf":"high","note":"Efnisien, called to fondle his nephew Gwern at the feast of reconciliation, throws the boy headlong into the fire — the act that ignites the battle and dooms both islands. The killing of the innocent child-king, handled by the Welsh with stark, unbearable brevity. <em>Realised in Movement V.</em>"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>S</strong> · Unnatural cruelty — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"S411","name":"The persecuted / banished wife (Branwen's blow)","cls":"S","branwen":{"passages":[3],"conf":"med","note":"Not calumny (as with Pwyll's Rhiannon) but scapegoating: to avenge Efnisien's insult on someone, Matholwch's court drives Branwen from the king's bed to the kitchen, where the butcher boxes her ear every day. Her three years of servile suffering — and the blow, <em>paluawt Branwen</em>, named in the colophon as one of the Three Unhappy Blows of Britain. (Thompson S411 is the banished/persecuted wife; S62 proper is &ldquo;cruel husband,&rdquo; so the application is filed here, conf <em>med</em>.) <em>Enters in Movement III.</em>"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>S</strong> · Unnatural cruelty — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"H411","name":"Chastity / virginity test","cls":"T","math":{"passages":[3],"conf":"med","note":"Math's wand-ordeal — step over the bent wand, \"and if you are a virgin, I shall know it.\" Aranrhod fails it on the spot, giving birth at the step. The magical virginity-test, with the foot-holder's required purity as its stake."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"T11.1","name":"Love from mere report","cls":"T","culhwch":{"passages":[1],"conf":"high","note":"Culhwch loves Olwen at the bare mention of her name, having never set eyes on her."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"T11.2","name":"Love from sight / love preceding the meeting","cls":"T","pwyll":{"passages":[3],"conf":"high","note":"Rhiannon to Pwyll on the Gorsedd: <em>I have wanted no man, and that for love of you</em>. She has loved him before he has seen her face; she has ridden to the Gorsedd specifically to find him. <strong>Compare Culhwch's T11.1</strong> (Culhwch loves Olwen at the bare mention of her name, having never seen her). Both Welsh tales open the marriage-quest with love preceding the meeting; both English tales begin with the marriage already in place or refuse the marriage altogether. Distinctively Welsh."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"T15","name":"Love at first sight","cls":"T","owain":{"passages":[4],"conf":"high","note":"Owain falls in love with the Countess at the sight of her in her husband's funeral procession — grief he himself caused. \"When he saw the woman, love of her kindled in him until it filled every part of him.\" The Welsh ties love and killing in a single stroke (\"the wife of the man you killed yesterday\"), the knot Luned will untie. The romance commonplace, here at its starkest; the same hinge drives Chrétien's <em>Yvain</em>."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"T231","name":"The widow wed to her husband's slayer","cls":"T","owain":{"passages":[4,5],"conf":"high","note":"The Countess will be argued into marrying the very man who killed her husband — not from fickleness (the medieval misogynist reading) but from necessity: the fountain must have a defender, and the strongest defender available is the man who beat the last one. The tale frames it as Luned's cold logic of survival, not the lady's weakness. <em>Realised across Mvt IV–V.</em>"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"T320","name":"Escape from undesired lover","cls":"T","gawain":{"passages":[3],"conf":"high","note":"The chamber scenes are formally escapes — through politeness, through deflection, through the language of fellowship — but they are escapes. Gawain never wins the encounter; he survives it."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"T331","name":"Chaste man tempted by woman, unsuccessful","cls":"T","gawain":{"passages":[3],"conf":"high","note":"Gawain's three refusals, each turned into a courtesy. The poem never lets him be discourteous; the failure, when it comes, is not in this column."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"T337","name":"The chaste host (refusal of the bride)","cls":"T","gawain":{"passages":[4],"conf":"med","note":"Bertilak invites Gawain back at the reveal — to accord with the lady \"who was your enemy keen.\" Gawain refuses by no means. The romance closes with no marriage, no return, and an explicit anti-marital catalogue (Adam, Solomon, Samson, David)."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"T338","name":"Chaste man tempted by woman, refusing — the chaste sleep","cls":"T","pwyll":{"passages":[2],"conf":"high","note":"Pwyll in Annwn beside Arawn's queen for a year, with her husband's full form upon him, the year-long licence and no observer. He turns away every night and says not a word. The Welsh prose registers no internal monologue, no struggle, no exposition — the act is reported as the natural consequence of <em>cedymdeithas</em> (companionship). <strong>Compare Sir Gawain's T331/T338</strong> in the three-day temptation by Lady Bertilak: there the test is explicit, the temptation is named, the hero half-fails. Two opposite vectors on the same family of codes — Welsh tradition's chaste-sleep is the test the hero doesn't know is being given; Gawain's is the test the hero knows about but is bound by exchange-of-winnings not to refuse."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"T481","name":"Adultery","cls":"T","math":{"passages":[5],"conf":"high","note":"Blodeuwedd and Gronw, lovers from the first look, betray and plot to murder Lleu. The tale does not moralise the love itself — there is real pathos in a being made for one man discovering a feeling no one conjured — but its fruit is murder, and the reckoning is total."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"T81.6","name":"Hero rescues abducted wife","cls":"T","orfeo":{"passages":[4,5],"conf":"high","note":"The exact action the international tale-type ATU 400 is named for. Sir Orfeo's version is structurally pure: no test of strength, no riddle, no third party — only the hero's musical performance, his correct ask, and the binding of the antagonist's own word."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>T</strong> · Sex, love & marriage — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"Z (Triads)","name":"Triadic references","cls":"Z","math":{"passages":[3,4,6],"conf":"high","note":"The branch threads three figures of the Welsh Triads through the tale: the Three Ill-Fated Blows (Gofannon's killing of Dylan), the Three Gold-shoemakers (Gwydion at Aranrhod's gate — the very Triad that names Manawydan), and the Three Disloyal War-Bands (Gronw's men who would not take his blow). The prose and the Triadic catalogue cross-referencing each other."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Z</strong> · Formulas & symbols — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"Z10","name":"End-formula: the refrain of the two ruined islands","cls":"Z","branwen":{"passages":[6],"conf":"med","note":"Branwen's dying words — <em>\"Alas that I was ever born: two good islands have been laid waste because of me\"</em> — and the colophon's tally (Ireland left with five pregnant women, Britain with seven men) give the branch its formulaic close: the marriage that should have joined two islands has emptied them both. Thompson Z10 &ldquo;formulistic framework&rdquo; / end-formula, rather than Z71's numeral-formulas. <em>Enters in Movement VI.</em>"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Z</strong> · Formulas & symbols — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"Z312","name":"The 'neither–nor' fatal condition","cls":"Z","math":{"passages":[5],"conf":"med","note":"Lleu can be killed only under impossible, liminal conditions — not in a house nor out, not on horse nor foot, by a spear a year in the making and worked only at the forbidden hour of Sunday mass, with one foot on a cauldron-rim and one on a buck. The hedged death of a god, a deep Indo-European pattern of the hero slain only at the threshold of every category."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Z</strong> · Formulas & symbols — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"Z71","name":"Formulistic numbers (three, nine)","cls":"Z","culhwch":{"passages":[2,3,7,10],"conf":"high","note":"Three shouts; nine nights and nine days; nine gates and nine porters; three-and-twenty brothers. The wonder-tale's arithmetic."},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Z</strong> · Formulas & symbols — carried by 1 of the nine tale."},{"code":"Z71.6","name":"Year and a day / a year from tonight","cls":"Z","pwyll":{"passages":[1,2,3,4,5],"conf":"high","note":"<em>Blwydyn y heno</em> — the Welsh formula for an appointed-meeting-in-a-year — is the structural beat of plot in Pwyll's First Branch (see M242 above for the count). Where Sir Gawain has <em>one</em> year-and-a-day (the Green Knight's return), Pwyll has at least four. Welsh narrative-arithmetic favours the year-and-a-day measure as the pulse against which kingship is conducted and bargains are sealed. (For the cross-tale layer, this is the clean comparative observation: the year-and-a-day is in all four tales, but Pwyll runs on it most densely.)"},"gloss":"Thompson <strong>Z</strong> · Formulas & symbols — carried by 1 of the nine tale."}];
window.PENDRAGON.motifClassNames = {"A":"Mythological","B":"Animals","C":"Tabu / interdiction","D":"Magic","E":"The dead","F":"Marvels & the Otherworld","G":"Ogres & giants","H":"Tests & tasks","J":"Wise & foolish","K":"Deceptions","L":"Reversals of fortune","M":"Ordaining the future","N":"Chance & fate","P":"Society","Q":"Rewards & punishments","R":"Captives & fugitives","S":"Unnatural cruelty","T":"Sex, love & marriage","V":"Religion","W":"Traits of character","Z":"Formulas & symbols"};
